<h2 id="split-vote">The Split Vote: What 3-1-1 Reveals</h2>

<p>The headline is the cut. The story is the vote: 3-1-1. Three members voted for the 150-basis-point cut. One voted for a smaller 75-basis-point cut. One voted to hold the rate unchanged.</p>

<p>This is not a technicality. The split reveals a fundamental disagreement within the MPC about the balance between two forces:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>The easing case (3 votes):</strong> Inflation at 3.3% is historically low. The real policy rate at 10.7% is deeply restrictive. GDP growth is strong. The economy needs lower borrowing costs to sustain momentum through the IMF exit transition.</li>
  <li><strong>The caution case (1 vote for 75bps):</strong> The direction is right, but 150bps is too aggressive given the Hormuz oil shock. Diesel up 25.7% will feed through to inflation within 60-90 days. A more gradual cut preserves room to respond.</li>
  <li><strong>The hold case (1 vote):</strong> With Brent at $112 and fuel prices spiking, cutting rates now risks having to reverse course in May if inflation accelerates. Better to wait for Q2 data.</li>
</ul>

<p>The dissenter who voted to hold was likely looking at the same data as the majority but weighting the Hormuz risk differently. In monetary policy, timing matters as much as direction. Cutting 150bps and then hiking in May would be worse for business confidence than holding at 15.5% and cutting later.</p>

