<p>The trajectory is dramatic: from 30% to 14% in less than three years. This is the fastest easing cycle in Ghana's modern monetary history, enabled by the equally dramatic inflation collapse from 50%+ to 3.3%.</p>

<h2 id="transmission-lag">Why Lending Rates Have Not Followed</h2>

<p>The policy rate is 14%. Commercial lending rates remain at 25-28%. This 11-14 percentage point gap is the transmission problem.</p>

<p>Why banks are not passing through the cuts:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Risk premium:</strong> Banks price in Ghana's macroeconomic history. A country that had 50% inflation two years ago does not get 16% lending rates immediately after stabilisation.</li>
  <li><strong>NPL overhang:</strong> Non-performing loans from the 2022-2023 crisis are still on bank balance sheets. Higher margins compensate for existing bad debt.</li>
  <li><strong>Government borrowing:</strong> T-bills at ~15% offer banks a risk-free return that is close to the policy rate. Why lend to SMEs at 20% with default risk when you can buy government paper at 15% risk-free?</li>
  <li><strong>Structural costs:</strong> Branch networks, cash handling, and compliance costs in Ghana are high relative to loan sizes.</li>
</ul>

<div class="risk-box">
  <h4>The Lending Rate Reality</h4>
  <p>A business borrowing GHS 500,000 (~$45,600) at 26% interest pays GHS 130,000 (~$11,850) per year in interest alone. At 14% (the policy rate), the same loan costs GHS 70,000 (~$6,380). The difference is GHS 60,000 ($5,470) per year, enough to hire two additional employees or fund three months of working capital.</p>
  <p>Until lending rates actually drop below 20%, the policy rate cut is a macro signal, not a business cost reduction.</p>
  <p><strong>When will lending rates drop?</strong> Historical pattern suggests 12-18 months after sustained low inflation and policy rate stability. If inflation stays below 5% through Q3 2026, lending rates may reach 22-24% by Q1 2027.</p>
  <p><strong>Confidence:</strong> MEDIUM (depends on inflation trajectory and banking sector competition)</p>
</div>

<h2 id="hormuz-complication">The Hormuz Complication</h2>

<p>The timing of the rate cut is complicated by the Hormuz crisis. Diesel prices rose 25.7% in one NPA pricing window. This cost increase will transmit through the economy over 60-90 days:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Month 1 (April):</strong> Transport fares increase. Generator costs rise. Fishing costs increase (diesel-powered trawlers).</li>
  <li><strong>Month 2 (May):</strong> Food prices adjust as transport costs feed through supply chains. Non-food inflation picks up.</li>
  <li><strong>Month 3 (June):</strong> Second-round effects. Wage pressure if food prices rise significantly. GSS inflation data reflects the full pass-through.</li>
</ul>

<p>The April and May inflation prints are the critical data points. If April inflation stays below 4.5%, the Hormuz pass-through is contained. If it jumps above 5%, the MPC's March cut looks premature, and the May decision becomes much harder.</p>

<h2 id="may-mpc">May MPC: The Most Consequential Decision</h2>

<p>The May 2026 MPC meeting is the single most important monetary policy event of the year. Three possible outcomes:</p>

