      <tr><td>Hormuz persists</td><td>Oil $95-110; inflation 4.5-6%</td><td>Hold at 14%</td><td>Cautious pause; wait for clearer data</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hormuz escalates</td><td>Oil above $110; inflation above 6%</td><td>Hold or hike 50-100bps</td><td>Tightening resumes; business confidence drops</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>

<h2 id="sector-impact">Sector-by-Sector Impact</h2>

<p><strong>Housing and Construction:</strong> The rate cut improves developer economics marginally, but mortgage rates at 28-35% remain prohibitive. A sustained rate below 12% would be needed to meaningfully expand mortgage access. The construction cost environment (inflation at 5.9%) is already favourable; the binding constraint is financing, not building costs.</p>

<p><strong>SME Credit:</strong> The transmission lag means SMEs will not see meaningful borrowing cost reductions for 12-18 months. Businesses that need credit now should budget for 25-28% rates through at least Q1 2027.</p>

<p><strong>Agriculture and Agro-Processing:</strong> Lower rates improve the economics of working capital financing, but only if banks actually lend at lower rates. The Hormuz-driven fuel cost increase partly offsets any interest cost reduction for energy-intensive processors.</p>

<p><strong>Financial Services:</strong> T-bill compression (91-day at ~15%) continues squeezing fixed-income returns. This drives the search-for-yield that inflated (and then crashed) the GSE. Banks' net interest margins face pressure as the policy rate falls but lending rates remain sticky.</p>

